- Command can be used with a string or index.
- To use with a string, -n flag is required to specify the the name of
the item to be modified. Currently, this will change the specified
information of all items with the same item name.

item as seen when list command is called.

The main logic is written functionally.

While there is nothing wrong with this approach, it goes against
the learning outcomes of this project.

Let's write our code in a more OOP manner instead.
Add additional attributes to Item class and parameters to add methods

interact with our product.

Let's,
* contribute towards maintaining a thorough user guide
* reference it frequently to ensure our implementations are consistent
  with stated behaviours

commitResults.messageTitle: Add exception handling to main logic
commitResults.messageBody:
run() benignly trusts user input and assumes it is a well-formed
request.

Handling malformed inputs would make our application more robust and
more accurately capture real world usage.

Let's work towards a more robust main class.

Malformed user inputs silently fail without indication to user.

Explicitly calling out such a case would allow users to correct their
input errors and try again.

Let's add explicit exception handling for a more user friendly
experience.

This reverts commit 312edc56a01bc0cfab62aab1920048716a88915e, reversing
changes made to 25326aa62cad72abe407fb02c53b8162aff679fc.

In our command classes, execute() returns a string for the Ui to print.

This is unintuitive and conveys no information about the success or
failure of the execution action.

Let's have execute() return its result status instead.

This would make it easier to write tests and assertions, aligning with
our goals for a more robust application.

Create new item classes; Update item class attributes

Commands are constructed with references to objects they need to
execute.

This increases our reliance on the Parser class to pass in the correct
objects. Additionally object specific actions such as save become harder to
decouple.

Add Commons CLI usage to Parser

I'll get started on the suggestions!

Individual command parsers are reliant on the main parser to function.
This has undesirable side effects such as reducing extensibility, and
requiring a separate instance of parser every time a command needs to be
parsed.

Reformating each parser into its own class allows new command parsers to be
added and the overall parser functionality to be more flexible.

Let's keep separate command parsers as separate parser objects, and make
use of the shared CommandOptionAdder to build future parsers.

commitResults.messageTitle: Improve parsers to handle malformed options

commitResults.messageBody:
Search takes in an unflagged string argument as input.

This makes it impractical to implement a search based on a field the
user wants to search through.

To allow searching through fields, lets work with a new search command
parser that provides the specifity we need.

The search method returns a string representation of one item based on
a single name field match. This is unintuitive and reduces code reusability.

It has been revamped to allow searching through arbitrary fields based
on the order of arguments passed in.

Let's try to call on this method for ItemList based operations,
overloading it with more specific argument fields as needed.

commitResults.messageTitle: Extract search methods into separate class
commitResults.messageBody:
The logic for searching through the inventory resides in the ItemList
class. This obscures it from use by other parts of the code that need
it.

By separating it into its own class, we have a common interface to build
upon other commands requiring search. In addition, the testability of
our code increases.

Let's further segment logical units of the ItemList to improve on
separation of concerns.

With the adoption of Apache commons for our parser class, the
InvalidArgumentException becomes no more expressive than a catch-all
InvalidCommandException.

Removing it cleans up our code and allow us to be more efficient with
our exceptions.

Let's work towards a more concise, expressive code base.

commitResults.messageBody:
Our parser now handles the check for negative quantities, meaning
RestockCommand is guaranteed to be given a positive quantity. Thus there
is no need for such a test.
